			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Take a cleric, a tank, and 3 dps classes. Add a bard. Now tell me a bard isn't a dps class</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
A bard isn't a DPS class.
<br />

<br />
A DPS class is a class that does damage. A bard doesn't do (much) damage, a bard enhances the performance of a group by means of buffing. If you consider a bard a dps class you should go ahead and call a chanter a DPS class for hasting the group with a haste buff. See next quote.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">if you remove the bard, you drop the groups dps by an amount at least as much as the dps as any one dps class was contributing</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
If your meleers click off their chanter haste and shammie buffs and whatnot you will also loose a lot of DPS. That doesn't make the original caster of those buffs a DPS class. With your reasoning you can call anything a DPS class, like (a bit more absurd but not by much) "the cleric keeps everyone alive so they can keep doing damage, therefore a cleric is a DPS class" or (slightly more in line but still out of whack) "the cleric casts spellhaste on the group so the nukers can nuke faster, therefore a cleric is a DPS class". Same thing with the bard. Buffing someone so <span style="font-style: italic">they</span> do more DPS doesn't make you a DPS class. Doing damage makes you a DPS class (hence the D in DPS, it stands for "damage").
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Citing Charm as a CC tool when the mobs are immune to it means it's not a CC tool.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
That is like saying that if you encounter a mob that is immune to mez, that mez is never a CC tool ever anywhere on any mob. Of course you can't charm-CC something that you can't charm, just like you can't slow mobs that are immune to slow. 
<br />
With mobs that <span style="font-style: italic">are</span> charmable it allows for taking an added mob out of the equation just like mez does, and even use it to keep a 3rd mob busy if you like. Charm just happens to be more risky with the chance of it breaking early etc., but also has advantages over mez (longer duration hence no need to replace a twisted song with mez, less target toggling, a bit of extra dps) and it's usually something of a personal preference whether or not to use it for CC in that way. There are plenty of times when bard charms can play a viable CC role.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Lull is not a crowd control tool. Lull is a pulling tool.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Valk already made the point about pulling being part of crowd-control. On top of that, lull is also useful for keeping roamers from agroing during a fight. I've used it for that pretty often, and most people never realize what happened and just go "/phew we're lucky that that mob didn't add". That kind of use is every bit as much CC as mezzing is.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Fade is not a crowd control tool. Fade is a pulling tool very occasionally, and a get out of jail free tool.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Fade is primarily a pulling tool, even though apparently SoE didnt intend it that way. Why do you think a lot of monks got so upset when Fade was introduced? Because bards died less? Nope, it was because bards were suddenly pulling like or more efficiently than monks in a lot of places. Fade allows bards to make pulls & splits that they could never do without it. You'd be surprised how often fades are done on pulls, not because the pulls are bad, but because pulling is smoother when you know how and when to use fade, and it becomes another tool in the toolbox.
<br />
Fade can also be used for taking care of a new (potential) add: agro it intentionally, lead it away, fade it off, and return to the group.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">"etc" is not a crowd control tool.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Really? <img src="images/smiles/icon_rolleyes.gif" alt="icon_rolleyes.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Bards don't have any other spells that let them actually CC a mob, except for snare.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Wrong. There are additional CC means for bards, some slightly unconventional. Creative use of Song of Highsun (mob-gate) can be used for CC in some circumstances. I've used it for that in PoN sometime for CC'ing a consort: spidy runs to the group, I gate it away, it comes running back, I gate it away, etc. until the group was ready to kill it. And as mentioned above, lull has CC uses as well on top of it already being a pulling tool. Then there's deftdance and even careful use of DA when you really need to keep that added mob busy for a short time.<br />_________________<br />Aeryon,
<br />
