			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Felicity gets the same number of resists as Bliss.  You can mez higher level mob, yes, thats always nice, but its just another upgrade.   Would be nice to see another in the rapture line (even with the gimp recast time) or an AE mez that lasts longer than 6 seconds (or more in the case of mez mastery.)  Yes, its an important upgrade, but pretty standard.  I suppose I should have stated that it doesnt exactly wow me anymore than C6 or Salik does.
<br />

<br />
As for tash, if there is a shaman or mage in the group, Id rely on their debuffing more than I would my tashing.  I agree that there is a LOT of content now (especially in GoD and OOW) where you NEED that debuffing first regardless and it's a race to get a mob slowed before it eats yer tank.  Im sure most shamans malo before they slow as well, though some may not.  
<br />

<br />
Shamans:
<br />
(63) Malosinia: Decrease Magic Resist by 70
<br />
(65) Malos: Decrease Magic Resist by 55
<br />

<br />
Mages:
<br />
(57) Malosini: Decrease Magic Resist by 60
<br />
(63) Malosinia: Decrease Magic Resist by 70
<br />

<br />
Enchanters:
<br />
(61) Howl of Tashan: Decrease Magic Resist by 48 (L61) to 50 (L64)
<br />
(60) Tashanian: Decrease Magic Resist by 37 (L57) to 43 (L68)
<br />

<br />
I often have a mage in my group and he often does his malo thing first and foremost, gaining little (if any) agro.  In cases where I am alone or if the mage is a chachi, I make my way around it fine.  It would be nice to have aggro-reducing effects for tash ALL the time, but the percentage theyre looking at isnt enough. Raise it and Ill take better note.  The point I was trying to make above all is that chanters can learn to control their aggro fine with the right tools.  
<br />

<br />
As for TOT, I use it still, along with Scryers Trespass.  I have them both up in OOW since everything under the sun seems to have mana.  I made mention that I thought it worked on PCs (bugged perhaps) not that I was missing Scryers Trespass, skank ho!  (grin)
<br />

<br />
Word of Morr.  I have used in the past and still use from time to time, but give me a stun over it any day.  Im not sure why a chanter would have aggro on 3-4 mobs at a time, unless theyre low on health or they were casting off AE tash (haha, which is kinda funny to imagine.)  Its good for charming and pet breaks, but in a group, Ive always single mezzed and had marked success with it.  
<br />

<br />
Now, all of that said, I will state that its a new ballpark when it comes to GoD and OoW.  You have 3 or 4 on even the biggest, best-equipped tank and he could be gone in the matter of seconds.  I can see where WoM could come in handy.  Though perhaps being a control freak, if we are lacking a monk or bard, its my job to pull and to make sure I keep things as controlled as I possibly can.  Having a Warrior run into a mess of mobs helter skelter in OoW or GoD zones and bringing back 7 mobs is a reality check.  Time to step in and pull for the group.  Perhaps its that I rarely see a need to use it except for specific instances.  
<br />

<br />
Will always agree that yet another rune is a waste.  Give us a focus effect that increases our charm duration, something more than just the same ole BLAH weve had in the past.  I guess if mana robes were worth a damn, this might be more interesting.  If it stacks, thats cool.  Ill use it, Im sure, but its not exciting, new or anywhere near as epic as I had hoped.  Just a personal preference.
<br />

<br />
---------------------- onto the overpowered Chanter ------------------
<br />

<br />
As for the people whining about enchanters being over-powered, I agree with Narith.  Ive never felt overpowered.  Our nukes suck.  Our dots are a joke.  Our pets are, well. as Akhbar would say theyre animations, not pets!  What we have going for us is:
<br />

<br />
Buffs
<br />
Mez
<br />
Charm
<br />

<br />
People look at our ability to charm and perhaps thats where the yer overpowered, d00ds thing comes in.  I rarely charm in groups, with the exception of play zones like chardok, the hole, velks, Luclin zones, GoD zones, etc.  I charm fight in HOH at times to get AAs.  I can usually get 1 AA an hour if I put my mind to it.  I also am lucky enough to have a pocket cleric on another account to rez my arse when things get ugly.  Charm soloing isnt all that, especially if you dont have another account to come pick up the pieces when things go haywire (which they do at the worst possible moment.)
<br />

<br />
Charm soloing (or two boxing as it may be in my case) is ok to get some experience now and then for AAs, but its boring, yer alone and even now its not the fastest way to make AAs.  
<br />

<br />
Mez.  Why is this overpowering?  Bards can do it.  Root-classes can park em just fine.  Shamans can slow up the wazoo now and you can have 2 or 3 in camp without much of a sweat.  I have a druid friend who 3-boxes and can root-cc like a madman.  You'll have to do more to convince me this is hugely overpowering.
<br />

<br />
Buffs.  We all got em.  You all want em.  Its nice to have C6 100% of the time.  Dont see how its overpowering.  Without Virtue and a few shaman buffs, Im as fragile as rice paper.  
<br />

<br />
Do enchanters have it easy?  Yeah, we do.  Funny thing is, I didnt pick this class to have it easy, to have buffs like C3 or to be able to charm-fight my way through the levels (which I didnt, I prefer groups above all.)  I liked the damn illusions.  Being a werewolf kicks ass.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /><br />_________________<br />Officer of <a href="http://pub86.ezboard.com/bveterancrew" target="_blank" class="postlink">Veteran Crew</a> 
<br />
<img src="http://www.alluveal.com/rose.jpg" border="0" />[/url]</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
