				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Lulu,
<br />

<br />
Your spell tables don't tell the whole story:
<br />

<br />
Shamans: 
<br />
(63) Malosinia: Decrease Magic Resist by 70, 3.25 sec cast, 2.25 recast, MR resist, 300 mana
<br />
(65) Malos: Decrease Magic Resist by 55, 5 sec cast, 10 sec recast, Unresistable, 400 mana
<br />

<br />
Mages:
<br />
(60) Mala: Decrease Magic Resist by 35, 5 sec cast, 10 recast, Unresistable, 350 mana
<br />
(57) Malosini: Decrease Magic Resist by 60, 3 sec cast, 2.25 recast, MR resist, 200 mana
<br />
(63) Malosinia: Decrease Magic Resist by 70, 3.25 sec cast, 2.25 recast, MR resist, 300 mana
<br />

<br />
Enchanters: 
<br />
(61) Howl of Tashan: Decrease Magic Resist by 48 (L61) to 50 (L64), 1 sec cast, 2.25 recast, Unresistable, 40 mana
<br />
(60) Tashanian: Decrease Magic Resist by 37 (L57) to 43 (L68), 1 sec cast, 2.25 recast, Unresistable, 40 mana
<br />

<br />

<br />
So, Tash is about 10 times as mana efficient as letting the mage/shaman do it.  Tash has a cycle time about 5 times faster than mala/malos.  Tash is unresistable, unlike the mage workhorse malosinia which often requires multiple casts and even a tash (gasp) to get it to stick.  Remember, sinia has the same or worse resist mod as slow so landing a sinia before slow is usually pointless.
<br />

<br />
In short, unless the chanter is getting pasted from tash agro it is far, far better for them to tash than not to tash!
<br />

<br />
Dd</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
