				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I don't think I explained it well enough, so the fault is mine  <img src="images/smiles/icon_sad.gif" alt="icon_sad.gif" border="0" />   I just happen to be one of those people who likes to tear apart how things work, while some others are content knowing that something does work...more a matter of play style and what makes your time more enjoyable  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  So here it goes again:
<br />

<br />
Damage does NOT equate to aggro...in alot of circumstances there can be a direct correlation that would suggest it, however factors that elevate or diminish damage frequently have no impact on aggro.  I will cite some examples:
<br />

<br />
Wether a warrior is using Defensive or MightyStrike their aggro is the same with both or neither.  He is using the same weapons, is attacking the same amount of times and is proccing at the same rate...therefore he generates the same hate...regardless of damage delivered.
<br />

<br />
A warrior with 2 1hb weapons with 0 skill generates the same aggro as a warrior with 2 1hs weapons with max skill with all variables being equal.
<br />

<br />
A warrior attacking a mob that is immune to their melee attacks generates the same aggro as if the mob were not.  IE non magical weapons on undead or non bane weapons on Emp still generate hate as if they were doing damage.
<br />

<br />
Attack buffs present have no impact on hate whatsoever except for a "slightly" adjusted rate of procs.  Mobs have low AC but high mitigation compared to players...its relatively easy to land procs on hits that have been reduced to 0 and register as misses.  A perfect illustration of that is Luclin mobs prior to acquiring enough innate attack to broach that threshold.  This explains the only slight adjustment to proc rates which would impact generated hate.
<br />

<br />
All that matters is number of attacks in a given time frame, adjusted by damage bonus, and damage "potential of the weapon"  
<br />

<br />
An example is a warrior using a 20/20 1hs in mainhand with a 14dmg modifier and 20/20 1hb in offhand both sans procs hasted to 100% and placed at level 65 skill levels would generate ~1.82 mainhand attacks and ~1.5 offhand attacks per combat round or 1 second.  By using pure hate spells cast in melee range a hate modifier was deduced of ~1.2...its not exact but its close enough for most purposes.  Average mainhand hate generated would be ( 20 + 14) x 1.2 x 1.82 = 74.25 hate per second.  Average offhand hate would be 20 x 1.2 x 1.5 = 36.  Hate per second without proc intervention or specials such as incite would be 110.25.
<br />

<br />
While for most players this level of detail isn't necessary it can let warriors know what aa selection or what weapons generate the most hate.  Any aa that adds attacks per second, increases either damage bonus, or increases the rate of triggered specials increases hate generated.
<br />

<br />
However we can now see how such affects as MightyStrike and Defensive don't affect aggro.  Nothing in the formula changes for either....MightyStrike just allows crits, and Defensive takes damage delivered and reduces its base modifier by 50%...however since raw damage delivered doesn't directly relate to aggro the warriors aggro remains unchanged for both.  Hate is determined PRIOR to any damage modifiers.
<br />

<br />
If you take this and apply it to charming there are 2 distinct paths that SoE could have taken with the nerf to charmed pets.
<br />

<br />
As Dd suggested that mob attack tables are altered and that a mob that typicall hits as if weilding 100/13 weapons the moment it was charmed would have offhand attacks disabled and its weapon values changed to ~40/13 weapons.  It would reduce hate generated from ~300 hate per second to ~67 hate per second.  It would be the smartest and most intuitive way do handle the charms...however this is SoE...
<br />

<br />
If SoE ignored any sense of prudence and simply disabled offhand triggers and then applied a base damage modifier to reduce the damage of the pet, similar to defensive, the damage results would be the same...however the pets hate generated would still be at its original values for its mainhand or ~168 hate per second or near 60% of its previous hate.
<br />

<br />
Its why I asked if anyone had tested the aggro to gain verification to see which of the 2 SoE had implemented.  If they implemented the latter then the pets dps would be 20% of previous but it would still fulfill the purpose that some chanters use when charming.  It would still generate aggro like a GoD mob without being armed even though its damage would be far less.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=220295" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="color: red">Valkargen MightyPuppy</span></a>
<br />
Elder Prophet Fashion Model of <a href="http://pub64.ezboard.com/billuminatis22903" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="color: blue">Illuminatis</span></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
