			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">A DPS class is a class that does damage. A bard doesn't do (much) damage, a bard enhances the performance of a group by means of buffing. If you consider a bard a dps class you should go ahead and call a chanter a DPS class for hasting the group with a haste buff. See next quote.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Grab a haste.  Go hunt for an hour.  Stop by your friendly chanter in an hour to get buff refresh.  The enchanter doesn't need to be in group to give out haste.
<br />
The bard on the other hand remains in the group the entire time giving out attack buffs, and overhaste, as well as their own melee damage.  If you remove the bard from the group, your group dps drops immediately.  With or without the enchanter, as long as you have the haste buff, you have the same dps.  Does purely all the dps a bard contributes come from his own direct melee?  Naw.  But when adding a bard to a group adds more dps to a group than adding any single dps class, then hell ya the bard is acting as a dps for the group.  Happens every time I want to add a bard instead of any other class to a group for adding dps.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">That is like saying that if you encounter a mob that is immune to mez, that mez is never a CC tool ever anywhere on any mob.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No, but if 100% of the mobs you fight are immune to mez, then you don't have a mezzer in your party.  If 100% of the mobs you fight are immune to slow, you don't have a slower in your party.  If every mob is immune to movement affecting spells, then you can't be pretend to be a CC class if you only have snare/root to CC.  If there was a zone that mobs never got tricked by feign death, then you wouldn't have a feign puller in your party.  When your trick doesn't work, you aren't in the group to provide the trick, you are there to provide other benefits.  When charm doesn't work, you obviously aren't using charm to CC, and you stop being a CC class if you rely on charm to CC.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">With mobs that <span style="font-style: italic">are</span> charmable it allows for taking an added mob out of the equation just like mez does</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Yup.  Just too bad it doesn't work anywhere, or it might be worthy of consideration.  Shaman can charm crocs in oasis too, but it doesn't mean we are a charm class.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Valk already made the point about pulling being part of crowd-control.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No he didn't.  Crowd control is about containing the <span style="font-style: italic">already</span> aggro mobs you have.  If it's not aggro, it's not a part of your crowd yet.  Lulling nearby mobs to keep them from adding isn't CC, it's prevention of CC.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">That kind of use is every bit as much CC as mezzing is.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Once that mob is aggro on you, lull does shit all to CC mobs.  A tool that prevents you from even having to CC the mob in the first place is not a CC tool, it's a preventative tool.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Creative use of Song of Highsun (mob-gate) can be used for CC in some circumstances.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
My bad.  I forgot about the 1 other tool bards have.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">And as mentioned above, lull has CC uses as well on top of it already being a pulling tool.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
As mentioned above, lull is not a CC tool, but a pulling tool, which is vastly different.
<br />
Please enlighten me as to how you use lull on the mobs that are beating down your healer...
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Then there's deftdance and even careful use of DA when you really need to keep that added mob busy for a short time.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Clerics can DA.  Monks can stonestance.  Shaman can click their sow boots and kite a mob away from camp.  None of those is a CC class.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=364111" target="_blank" class="postlink">Juujuu Bigmojo</a>
