				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Juujuu wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">No he didn't. Crowd control is about containing the already aggro mobs you have. If it's not aggro, it's not a part of your crowd yet. Lulling nearby mobs to keep them from adding isn't CC, it's prevention of CC.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Considering the nature of the discussion in regards to Enchanter Crowd Control rolls in groups, thats just self serving arguementative sophistry.
<br />

<br />
First you argue that bards are indeed a DPS class...that they directly increase the ability of other classes present proportionally to add to DPS totals.  That the very nature of their buffs are short term in benefit and makes them required to be in the group to actually garner this benefit.  Your conclusion is that bards are a DPS class.
<br />

<br />
Then you argue that pulling and lull variants are not CC...even though they have the same direct relationship to CC that bards do to DPS. 
<br />

<br />
Bards affect DPS...your conclusion then is that they are DPS.  Pulling affects crowd control, and even removes the need for it...your conclusion then is that they aren't CC /boggle
<br />

<br />
Pulling is and always has been a form of passive CC.  Your are actively controlling how many mobs the group will be fighting at any given time, ie how many mobs will be given the option of beating on your cleric.  Active CC is then the ability to control actively aggro mobs present in camp.  They are directly related because one DIRECTLY impacts the other...and can reduce or completely remove the need of a group to have active CC.  To even suggest, when a direct correlation has been proven in practice, that they are separate entities and aren't part of the same equation is silly.
<br />

<br />
This is the arguement of enchanters as relating to this discussion.  If the need for active crowd control is removed, then that capacity no longer needs to be addressed in group composition.
<br />

<br />
Enchanters, in heavy numerical crowd control situations, are the best CC class in game.  Bards are limited to at most 2 or 3 mobs being simultaneously crowd controlled, and during this time proportionally reduces their terciary group benefits.  Enchanters can exceed that number.  It can involve risk, however other classes can aid them in that function...shammies for additional debuffing and aggro splitting, necros for feeds, a high mana regen group structure, bards for pre-mez, and the list goes on.
<br />

<br />
However in zones with large mob displacement and with passive CC tools available, frequently CC group requirements can be reduced to allow the group to use other tools available to them or reduce active CC requirments to 0.  
<br />

<br />
This is the crux of the enchanter arguement regarding CC in relation to current content.  To argue that passive tools are not crowd control, when it directly impacts active crowd control needs of a group, and class desireability in actual game practice, is nothing more than theoretical debate and ignores every in game circumstance...which is actually what is affecting the enchanter class atm.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=220295" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="color: red">Valkargen MightyPuppy</span></a>
<br />
Elder Prophet Fashion Model of <a href="http://pub64.ezboard.com/billuminatis22903" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="color: blue">Illuminatis</span></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
