			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Does purely all the dps a bard contributes come from his own direct melee?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Yes, that and any DoTs/DD's he may be using. That's the definition of DPS: damage that <span style="font-style: italic">you</span> do per second. Anything indirectly upping someone else's dps does not make you a dps class or contribute to the dps that you're doing yourself.
<br />
A DPS class is a class that does damage, that's their role.  They will do good damage regardless of the makeup of the group, and possibly fulfil that role better with a selection of nice buffs. A bard doesn't work that way. If a bard had been a DPS class you could make a dps-group with (for example) one cleric, one tank and 4 bards. Fun though it'd be, that's not a DPS group.
<br />
What you're describing is how a bard enhances group performance, which was my point all along. Some possible effects of doing that are 
<br />
* dps'ers will do more dps 
<br />
* mobs will do less damage 
<br />
* PC spells will land better
<br />
* NPC spells will land less
<br />
* group will regen more mana & hp
<br />
Notice that just 1 of those is about DPS. What a bard does to a group is to allow the whole group to shift up a gear or two by making it run more efficiently. This translates to fewer medbreaks and steadier & faster killrates. A bard does that with short-duration buffs, other classes achieve that with long(er) duration ones. The role is still the same: group buffage/enhancement, not dps. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When charm doesn't work, you obviously aren't using charm to CC, and you stop being a CC class if you rely on charm to CC. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
That's very different from "Charm is not a CC tool because in certain places you can't use it", which is what you basically stated before. The point is that where charm <span style="font-style: italic">is</span>avaible, it can be used for CC.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">As mentioned above, lull is not a CC tool, but a pulling tool, which is vastly different.
<br />
Please enlighten me as to how you use lull on the mobs that are beating down your healer... </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I use it to not make the mob beat on the healer in the first place. I could as well use mez for it if I choose to, but lull has (in this case) the same effect, and adds the benefit of not having to deal with the mob once it wanders off. It takes the mob out of the equation same way as if it had been mezzed or charmed. Whether the crowd is already agroed or not is a moot point - lull allows you to have control over it before it agroes, mez/charm/other stuff lets you take care of it after the agroing.
<br />

<br />
Another example: say there are a couple of (see-invis) mobs somewhere that I want the group to pass without fighting them. Here's a few ways of how I can go about it:
<br />
1) Mez them all, keep them mezzed until group has passed, then fade.
<br />
2) Agro them all, kite them a few miles away until group has passed, then fade.
<br />
3) Use lull on the mobs and let group pass.
<br />
You're saying that when I use the mez (or even kite) method, I'm doing CC, and when I'm using lull, I'm not doing CC. Yet I'm doing the exact same thing, namely controlling mob behaviour and keeping mobs from attacking the group. Any of those methods (or combinations) lets my group pass the mobs without having to fight them.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Clerics can DA. Monks can stonestance. Shaman can click their sow boots and kite a mob away from camp. None of those is a CC class</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I didn't say that those tools define a CC class, I simply pointed out that they can be used to CC with, in addition to the methods already mentioned. Those classes are not CC classes no, because they lack the main tool(s) for CC. They do however, as you pointed out, have limited CC capabilities. Same goes for druids, wizards, rangers, and prolly some I forgot, who can use snare/root to kite or park mobs. That too is CC, even though it doesn't make them CC classes. It's a little bit like...well...like a bard boosting a group's DPS while not actually being a DPS class <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /><br />_________________<br />Aeryon,
